<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-983-632  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 983 632.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Today's Office  Oct 1989 v24 n5 p6(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The maturing of database management systems.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ambrosio, Johanna.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Data base management systems (DBMS) can be flat-file managers,which let users work on only one computer file at a time, orrelational systems, which permit simultaneous retrieval ofinformation from different files.andP;  The distinction between thesetwo types of DBMS software is fading, and DBMSs are becomingeasier to use.andP;  Vendors are striving to make their desktop DBMSproducts compatible with IBM's Structured Query Language (SQL),which offers a standard way of interacting with databases.andP;  Thereis also DBMS growth in the area of microcomputer networking, andvendors are solving problems of slow network response times byusing client-server architecture.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Data Base Management SystemsTrendsVendorsEnd Users.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>